commit_message:
Mounting changed shares on cluster update

When we update the shares on a cluster, we are now
calling the mount_shares routine anytime we have
new or changed shares so that the shares will be
mounted.  Unmounting of shares will be handled in
another patch.

Change-Id: I3456ea089f9eb005c842aa3a43bdce6da5daafe0
Partial-Implements: bp sahara-add-shares-to-clusters

[{'created': '2015-09-29 17:18:07.000000000', 'message': "[WIP] Configuration Resource

This updates, and replace, the $$configuration resource, in order to
increase test coverage, and to change its behavior to match ngResource.
Four methods of configuration are explicitly tested. First, explicitly
setting a cloud configuration during application config time. Secondly,
autodetection of available services using the default URL's provided by
those services. Thirdly, loading a server-provided config.json file.
Lastly, user-defined configurations provided at runtime.

Eslint was updated as well, as the indentation rules did not seem to work
too well with functions in function parameters being declared in a second
line.

Change-Id: I345b6f8e5da9d3064eabb3cc8cf0113e59626ac5
"}, {'created': '2015-10-01 23:52:43.000000000', 'message': "[WIP] Configuration Resource

This splits configuration management into two components, each with
a separate purpose. The first, $$configuration, acts as an ngResource-style
API abstraction that loads and maintains the list of currently active
configurations. The second, $$selectedConfiguration, provides the
mechanism by which a specific configuration is selected and validated.

New features added:
- A configuration may be force-loaded into the $$configuration provider
  during app initialization.
- The autodetection mechanism has been renamed to 'default'.
- The localStorage, configFile, and default detection mechanism may
  now be enabled or disabled (default disabled).

The main drive for this is separation of concerns and testability. When
writing tests for downstream API's, having to navigate the complex chain of
promise resolutions simply to load an API test configuration was
obnoxiously difficult. Separating selection and loading greatly simplifies
this. Furthermore, adopting a more ngResource-style resolution of
resources - where the object returned from a CRUD request will be the actual
data object in use, also simplifies usage in the user interface.

Tests have been provided, and testing threshold has been updated accordingly.

Eslint was updated as well, as the indentation rules did not seem to work
too well with functions in function parameters being declared in a second
line.

Change-Id: I345b6f8e5da9d3064eabb3cc8cf0113e59626ac5

commit_message:
Configuration Resource

This splits configuration management into two components, each with
a separate purpose. The first, $$configuration, acts as an ngResource-style
API abstraction that loads and maintains the list of currently active
configurations. The second, $$selectedConfiguration, provides the
mechanism by which a specific configuration is selected and validated.

New features added:
- A configuration may be force-loaded into the $$configuration provider
  during app initialization.
- The autodetection mechanism has been renamed to 'default'.
- The localStorage, configFile, and default detection mechanism may
  now be enabled or disabled (default disabled).

The main drive for this is separation of concerns and testability. When
writing tests for downstream API's, having to navigate the complex chain of
promise resolutions simply to load an API test configuration was
obnoxiously difficult. Separating selection and loading greatly simplifies
this. Furthermore, adopting a more ngResource-style resolution of
resources - where the object returned from a CRUD request will be the actual
data object in use, also simplifies usage in the user interface.

Tests have been provided, and testing threshold has been updated accordingly.

Eslint was updated as well, as the indentation rules did not seem to work
too well with functions in function parameters being declared in a second
line.

Change-Id: I345b6f8e5da9d3064eabb3cc8cf0113e59626ac5

commit_message:
Update /versions related API description

Add /versions (with HTTP 200 response)
Fix / response code
  remove 200 response for '/' (i.e keep HTTP 300 response)
Update version response example (adds v2.3/v3.0)
Remove comment out XML description.

Ref.
Source Code for URL definition
  https://github.com/openstack/glance/blob/master/etc/glance-api-paste.ini
Source Code for URL handling
  https://github.com/openstack/glance/blob/master/glance/api/middleware/version_negotiation.py
  https://github.com/openstack/glance/blob/master/glance/api/versions.py
Test code for response
  https://github.com/openstack/glance/blob/master/glance/tests/functional/test_api.py

Changes
  Don't return 300 when requesting /versions
  https://github.com/openstack/glance/commit/3fc253c197095f5f09846855a755b677ec37deb5

Change-Id: Id7052ece6a120bf63b086910460b57a7d0e7e15b
Closes-Bug: #1515022
Closes-Bug: #1404857

& Services
* Tokens

I'm against this fix. If some different service need haproxy to be setted up - it must do it by itself, not using manifests from other services, cause those manifests could easily contain service-related settings. As a result if we will want to introduce some options in haproxy related to exact service (like we already have, btw, for horizon in ssl class declaration) - it must be done in separate manifest.

So I propose to create his own haproxy manifest for author of Zabbix plugin instead of use Horizon one."}, {'account_id': 16771, 'date': '2015-11-19 14:24:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 7075, 'date': '2015-11-19 15:20:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

agree, it is really hazardous to modify haproxy configuration file used by another service'}, {'account_id': 16771, 'date': '2015-11-20 14:24:57.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

It would be a straight way to move zabbix plugin haproxy confs into separate files.'}]

commit_message:
Make webservice as common for haproxy conf

Get rid of "horizon" name in haproxy configuration so other services will
be able to employ common webservice as well.

Change-Id: I75b732420a769bde7910632e5c3d2790c9ac41c5
Related-Bug: #1517005

commit_message:
Move label formatting to make_fs from driver

The code that truncated and formatted labels was in driver - too high up
in code hierarchy. The label is now simply passed to make_fs and it
handles it properly.

Change-Id: I87c151e4f01784101977bdd46c3e64401090fc05
Closes-Bug: #1505621

commit_message:
Add support of os_service_default fact in glance spec

   This change adds possibility to use the os_service_default
   fact for configuration options that default to '<SERVICE DEFAULT>'.
   this change is done by analogy with cinder
   commit 667e6c0850672dbbf99381eb92468f95e5591913

Change-Id: Ie5c8909bcc1c9a6a7a9ab1b59eec4637751ffd74

commit_message:
Re-assembling bond

* Now we only re-assemble bond if we change bond mode. Before we re-assembled
bond every puppet run, that is not needed and sometimes led to kernel panic.
* Refactor bond downing and upping behaviour during configuration:
we only down and up bond if we change bond configuration, if nothing is
changed - we do nothing.

Change-Id: Ie9d15c7474c27dd396ae5e46cf0e41ff25786574
Closes-bug: #1507613

commit_message:
Release 1.11.0 of os-client-config

Adds the ability to handle legacy env-var prefixes, as well as fixing
a bug in non-float timeout values being passed to swift.

Needed-By: If1656214d17d32c5724bc5bb7faa6df85b311bb6
Change-Id: Ia0930c6bb2e33fb0dcaaa66da22cf2ddfcae8113

commit_message:
utils.build: added helper functions for bootstrap images

* make_targz
* run_script_in_chroot
* recompress_initramfs - rebuilds initramfs image in the chroot
* run_mksquashfs - runs mksquashfs available in the chroot
* get_installed_packages - lists packages installed in the chroot
* copy_kernel_initramfs - copy/move kernel and initramfs from the chroot

Change-Id: I49eb92f0dc0303e35d7630d7690b0004a2018ccf
Implements: blueprint dynamically-build-bootstrap

commit_message:
Site create RPC

Implement site create RPC. Now tricircle api can utilize RPC
to notify cascade service to start rpc server for new site.

Partially implements: blueprint implement-api
Ref: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/tricircle/+spec/implement-api

Change-Id: I73879a84d31b5ac9004cfe3f18cb9a984d53099c

commit_message:
Add OpenContrail driver

That version uses the key/value store exposed by the OpenContrail
API but that's not efficient. The BGP/VPN resources and sub-association
need to be added to the OpenContrail data model.

That first PoC will be delivered to with the Liberty release but will be
replaced by a final one for Mitaka and next releases without any
migration script or method from the first PoC version.

Implements: blueprint opencontrail-bgpvpn-driver
Change-Id: I3795dd7b24afdac1cd5134c41b6b32ef8a888287

commit_message:
Fix path to nailgun-agent

nailgun-agent package was updated and agent was renamed to
nailgun-agent [1, 2]. So we need to update path both for
CentOS and Ubuntu packages

[1]. https://github.com/openstack/fuel-nailgun-agent/blob/master/specs/fuel-nailgun-agent.spec#L37
[2]. https://github.com/openstack/fuel-nailgun-agent/blob/master/debian/rules#L12

Change-Id: Ia9ecdd96bb2eb989c2bcfb3cd51efbfd12e8f9ea
Closes-bug: #1492449

carbonara: optimize _first_block_timestamp

using Pandas.

Rename dbsync to upgrade

The tool is actually used to upgrade the indexer, and might be later
used to upgrade the storage engine too.

Change-Id: I7266397209e814dec5eb732804bcdc022943b33d

subject: Set bash interpreter explicitely for ci hooks
revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-20 11:57:02.000000000', 'message': "Set bash interpreter explicitely for ci hooks

CI config requires explicit definition of bash interpreter.
So, we need to add explicit definition to one of three files
that are used in CI jobs - 'contrib/ci/common.sh'.

Change-Id: Ie387ac778ad65811e734bba41c9525bda3913cd9
"}]
commit_message:
Set bash interpreter explicitely for ci hooks

CI config requires explicit definition of bash interpreter.
So, we need to add explicit definition to one of three files
that are used in CI jobs - 'contrib/ci/common.sh'.

Change-Id: Ie387ac778ad65811e734bba41c9525bda3913cd9

commit_message:
Specifying target provision states in fsm

In ironic, a state can be associated with a target state, and these
associations are defined when the fsm is created. This patch adds
the ability to override these default target states when initializing
the fsm as well as when processing an event that transitions the fsm
to a new state (and target state).

This is useful, for example, when adding the manual clean feature,
which causes a node to go from manageable -> clean* -> manageble
instead of the default behaviour (for automated cleaning) of
-> clean* -> available.

Change-Id: I0a7c9be0e44b75f8bd2ebfefd3fb710109612578
Implements: blueprint manual-cleaning

commit_message:
Fix metadata storage

After recent changes BackupJob.get_metadata also returns information about storage.
But before this patch, I was replacing conf.storage from string (swift, local, ssh) to actual object (SwiftStorage, LocalStorage, SshStorage).
So in get_metadata we were trying to serialize object instead of string.
 This patch fixes that by leaving conf.storage as a string and providing to Job storage as dedicated parameter.

Incompatibilities: tests/test_job.py

Change-Id: I0869b7d432e8f8a7f0839e4670a8845bf932e69c
(cherry picked from commit 5d577d043a4c192a8446b930447dafef0ad586dc)

commit_message:
Support arguments for clean step methods

With this change, a clean step method used for manual cleaning can take
keyword arguments.

This adds an optional argsinfo parameter to the clean_step decorator.
Its value is a dictionary of keyword arguments where key is the name
of the argument and value is a dictionary as follows:
- ‘description’: <description>. This should include possible values.
- ‘required’: Boolean. True if this argument is required. If so, it
  must be specified in the clean request; false if it is optional.

Change-Id: I3bcf1a5a91f06b19d917be2bf7acb035801f9193
Implements: blueprint manual-cleaning

commit_message:
Validate all tcp/udp port numbers

We introduced a common port validation method
validate_network_port, this patch try to validate
all port parameters using it.

Change-Id: I209b89d2a4c2bbc5619d058f78da2f5f76d1723c

commit_message:
Compatibility with a coming puppet-heat fix

There is a fix coming into puppet-heat to ensure correct dependencies
within heat::keystone::domain class. This means the relationship with
Keystone_domain[heat_domain] will stop working. We should depend on the
whole class instead.

Change-Id: Ic541f11978908f9344e5590f3961f0d31c04bb0c
Depends-On: I9078be31f26e454e0686debcefa070721767a581

commit_message:
WIP: domain_name defines the Keystone_domain resource name

Before I9078be31f26e454e0686debcefa070721767a581 the Keystone_domain
resource was always named 'heat_domain'.

We customize the domain_name into 'heat_stack' instead [1]

1. https://github.com/openstack/instack-undercloud/blob/master/elements/puppet-stack-config/puppet-stack-config.yaml.template#L93

Change-Id: I28cda7506439c8bb5644107f529c14d07ecc030e
Closes-Bug: 1518286

commit_message:
Support unmounting shares on cluster update

When we update the shares on a cluster, we are now
calling the unmount_shares routine anytime we have
removed shares from the cluster.

Change-Id: Id028df9d09b8d603500b80af14fdf3be2ddde4d3
Partial-Implements: bp sahara-add-shares-to-clusters

Steve: Do I correctly understand, that current approach still have issue with re-authentication on delete?
Also afaik, Oleksii in vacation during this week, so I thing, that he will take a look on it only on the next week.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-10-19 17:25:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Sergey: Yeah, that's one of several issues actually, turns out making this work properly is pretty difficult!

I'm still working through the issues and will update this patch soon - I'm not sure how much more time I can spend on this in the near future, but I'm happy to collaborate with Oleksii when he returns from vacation and work out the best path forward."}, {'account_id': 7256, 'date': '2015-10-19 23:39:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Haven't tested this, but some deployments don't expose username/password to the running service (token auth only). This might not be an issue with v3 and trust context, but just wanted to make sure this was considered."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-10-20 07:35:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> Haven't tested this, but some deployments don't expose username/password to the running service (token auth only). 

That shouldn't be an issue unless you try to use this combined with deferred_auth_method=password.  Since trusts are the default now, switching to the stored context via a trust should work fine with token-only-auth (in fact that's one of the main reasons it's a much better default than password :)

I'd hold off testing this for now - I'm still working through some issues because this still leaks trusts under certain circumstances (similar to Oleksii's original patch) - I think there's going to be a significant rework to fix that, so I'll remove the WIP when this is ready for wider testing."}, {'account_id': 12363, 'date': '2015-10-26 10:53:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

The problem with deletion is that we try to instantiate keystoneclient after deletion of the trust here https://github.com/openstack/heat/blob/master/heat/engine/stack.py#L1407 Workaround, that works for me in my devstack installation is to move https://github.com/openstack/heat/blob/master/heat/engine/stack.py#L1405-L1413 before place where we delete trust https://github.com/openstack/heat/blob/master/heat/engine/stack.py#L1360 .'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-11-20 11:24:30.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Obsoleted by https://review.openstack.org/#/c/226384/'}]

commit_message:
Cleanup baymodel operations in conductor api

Cleanup baymodel operations in conductor/api.py which are never
been called.

Magnum do not need to call conductor (rpc call) to do any operation
for baymodel. All baymodel related operations are DB operation.

Closes-Bug: #1517338
Change-Id: If5078efd71eaf57b8700e0c8097c89386583cf02

commit_message:
Add a function to generate fernet keys for keystone.

- "generate_fernet_keys" function was added to generate fernet keys
for keystone. For key generation was used "openssl" tool.

Implements blueprint: fernet-tokens-support

Change-Id: Ia80c554b8514adc103ccbd8310b696d2357bfe96

commit_message:
Enable libvirt AppArmor protection

This is Security vulnerability fix. libvirt AppArmor protection should be
enabled by default.

It enables apparmor security_driver in libvirt/qemu and disables Unix domain
sockets protection in the AppArmor for libvirt only for Ubuntu Linux.

Change-Id: I75a35b5602028b04e0f547b06eff29d9dbf43a6b
Doc-Impact: ops
Closes-Bug: #1509314

This really isn't any of my business, but Murano proved early on a ton of repos for one project that were all related in behavior was an anti-pattern."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-11 16:38:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-governance-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/66/244166/2/check/gate-governance-docs/9eecb0e//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 40s'}, {'account_id': 7353, 'date': '2015-11-11 16:46:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

The OpenStack Ansible project is embarking on moving the various roles within our project into separate repositories to enable the use of the greater ansible galaxy deployment pattern (which is an Ansible best practice) and has been asked for repeatedly in the community to enable others to consume the work that we've done as standalone resources. Additionally, the changes being worked on within the project follow prior art from Chef and Puppet where the chef-cookbooks and puppet-modules have been broken out into separate repositories. Being that none of these repositories are related in behavior and that we're looking to be more deployer friendly / Ansible-centric I don't think lessons learned in Murano apply here."}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2015-11-11 17:53:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Code-Review

Removing -1 vote since Puppet seems to not be suffering from multi-repo overload and that is the closest analog to OSAD (not Murano).

Still i think you will regret it long term.

Regards

-steve'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2015-11-13 05:36:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

Backing up Kevin's point, the separation of ansible roles for inclusion in galaxy is a standard practice in the ansible community, and would help increase adoption by ansible users.

However, I don't believe it necessitates separate _repositories_. For an example of many roles in a single repository, you can look at openstack/bifrost/playbooks/roles/*

If the OpenStack-Ansible project leaders want to use seprate repos, I don't see the harm in it."}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-11-16 14:20:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1 Rollcall-Vote+1

This updates governance for new roles that will be coming online
as the OpenStack-Ansible moves to break out our roles from the
main repo.

commit_message:
os-vif: add openstack/os-vif repository under Nova team

os-vif is a project to define an object model and plugin system
to integrate OpenStack network providers (eg Neutron) and
OpenStack compute providers (eg Nova)

It will be developed jointly by representatives from both the
Nova and Neutron teams, but for the sake of governance Nova is
set as the owner.

Change-Id: Ife95bea0cba68901a8c820c4f32a9782d5735beb
Depends-on: Ifc2c1a3198075aafc3fd97f0c5355eb27ba8bc19

commit_message:
Add assert:supports-rolling-upgrade to nova

Nova has:
 - Asserted assert:supports-rolling-upgrade
 - Has a defined plan for operators to upgrade individual compute resources
   separately from control services, eliminating the need to restart the
   entire deployment all at once.
 - Has had full-stack testing of mixed-version mid-upgrade services in its
   gate consistently for several releases.

Change-Id: I79e50b2345adeb15d729f348c36b6a5808dfa37d

[{'created': '2015-11-10 21:45:03.000000000', 'message': "Add assert:supports-upgrade to nova

Nova has stable configuration changes, database schema upgrades, a defined
upgrade process that doesn't change, and always includes upgrade details
in the release notes. These statements have been consistently true for
the last several cycles.

Change-Id: I31d0f50fe4e7864dd8ef505c429f9df40520f238
"}]
commit_message:
Add assert:supports-upgrade to nova

Nova has stable configuration changes, database schema upgrades, a defined
upgrade process that doesn't change, and always includes upgrade details
in the release notes. These statements have been consistently true for
the last several cycles.

Change-Id: I31d0f50fe4e7864dd8ef505c429f9df40520f238

[{'created': '2015-11-19 23:01:05.000000000', 'message': "Fix floating ip setting name in samples

The sample files reference the setting 'use_floatingip' which never
gets set, as the code is looking for 'use_floating_ip' instead.

Change-Id: If55b3ac6722e13886f09cce09cf2c4cc0fb73f77
"}]
commit_message:
Fix floating ip setting name in samples

The sample files reference the setting 'use_floatingip' which never
gets set, as the code is looking for 'use_floating_ip' instead.

Change-Id: If55b3ac6722e13886f09cce09cf2c4cc0fb73f77

Infra: http://tempsend.com/42488FF12F/D452/infra.svg'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-10-09 10:22:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

I think there are an issue with this visualization: it conflates project teams and deliverables (if they happen to share the same name).

People already have a hard time to understand what we mean by "project team" and "deliverable", and this confuses things further. In the viz, "nova" represents both the project team and the main deliverable. For "infrastructure",  the circle doesn't represent a deliverable (it represents the project team). How about representing teams and deliverables in different shapes, and show that the nova team produces the nova deliverable ?'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-10-09 10:24:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Also feature request: show the repositories that make up a deliverable.'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-10-09 14:18:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Sure, I can try different shapes for deliverables and teams.

As for the repo, I don't think dot handles hyperlinks so well. But I can see, did u think that the bubbles should be clickable -> repo?"}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-10-09 14:22:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

As for the conflating part:

In the code:

  def skip_deliverable(project_name, deliverable_name):

If a project produces a deliverable with its own name, it isn't included in the graph, so I don't think there is any conflating here. But I might be wrong :-P"}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-10-09 15:35:12.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-10-09 15:36:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

With diamonds:

Infra: http://tempsend.com/44D56E1EE3/A632/infra.svg

All: http://tempsend.com/1F392B692C/1FFD/os.svg'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-09 15:43:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-governance-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/29/232729/5/check/gate-governance-docs/be4b207//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 58s'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-10-12 10:43:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

@Josh: I just don't think you should skip some deliverables, just because they happen to share the same name as the team name.

That is confusing because you are then missing some deliverables (or are supposed to magically know which of them are skipped). If all teams had a deliverable with their own name that would be kind of OK... but it's not the case. Someone looking at TripleO for example can't really tell if that team produces a "tripleo" deliverable or not.'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-10-12 16:16:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Sounds fine with me, will tweak this to not skip any :)'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-10-12 18:08:48.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-12 18:16:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified+1

Thanks for the updates.  This doesn't seem to be working for me.  Here's what I did.

    $ python tools/universe_dot.py reference/projects.yaml os_universe.dot
    ...
    $ neato -Tsvg os_universe.dot > os_universe.svg
    Error: os_universe.dot: syntax error in line 1 near 'Universe'

    $ python tools/universe_dot.py reference/projects.yaml neutron_universe.dot neutron
    ...
    $ neato -Tsvg neutron_universe.dot > neutron_universe.svg
    Error: neutron_universe.dot: syntax error in line 1 near 'Universe'

The generated dot files are here: http://paste.openstack.org/show/478316/

It seems if I put quotes the diagram name, like "Neutron Universe", it fixes the error.'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-11-10 00:53:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

Which pydot did u install, can u make sure u install pydot2, pydot is somewhat abandoned and pydot2 I've had better luck with (pydot2 seems to fix this afaik)..."}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-11-10 00:53:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

[{'created': '2015-10-08 19:59:42.000000000', 'message': 'Add a tool that allows visualizing the projects as a graph

This tool, when ran can create diagrams that show what
exactly the big-tent is and/or what the subprojects/deliverables
a project produces are.

For example, here is the way to create a output for ironic
and its deliverables:

$ python tools/universe_dot.py  reference/projects.yaml \
  ironic_universe.dot ironic;
$ dot -Tsvg ironic_universe.dot  > ironic_universe.svg

Then view svg as is, or convert to png or other:

Output for ironic (in png format):

http://i.imgur.com/5nf9z9u.png

This requires pydot2 and pyyaml to be installed to work.

Change-Id: Idcd73f9e678e200d65eda4d1d54f1156fd18853b

commit_message:
Add a tool that allows visualizing the projects as a graph

This tool, when ran can create diagrams that show what
exactly the big-tent is and/or what the subprojects/deliverables
a project produces are.

For example, here is the way to create a output for ironic
and its deliverables:

$ python tools/universe_dot.py  reference/projects.yaml \
  ironic_universe.dot ironic;

$ neato -Tsvg ironic_universe.dot > ironic_universe.svg

Then view svg as is, or convert to png or other...

This requires pydot2 and pyyaml to be installed to work.

Change-Id: Idcd73f9e678e200d65eda4d1d54f1156fd18853b

Add link for a top page of document to "Contents" in sidebar

It is useful to have a convenient way to return a top page
of a document. Readers can easily access a toc of a document.

commit_message:
Refactor of keystone_domain provider.

This remove the @@default_domain_id from the code.  It is no longer
necessary to have a global class variable sharing this id.  All is now
encapsulated inside the keystone_domain class.

The change come mainly from the new policy regarding default domain[1]
which simplifies the logic, and the code.

[1] https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/keystone_no_domain

Change-Id: I71ab37165db6b0fe8472e7dfc8abcf72e0caac4a

commit_message:
Fix metadata storage

After recent changes BackupJob.get_metadata also returns information about storage.
But before this patch, I was replacing conf.storage from string (swift, local, ssh) to actual object (SwiftStorage, LocalStorage, SshStorage).
So in get_metadata we were trying to serialize object instead of string.
 This patch fixes that by leaving conf.storage as a string and providing to Job storage as dedicated parameter.

Change-Id: I0869b7d432e8f8a7f0839e4670a8845bf932e69c

commit_message:
Explicitly set fuel-library version to PRODUCT_VERSION

This works around a case where fuel-library has multiple
versions available, but we only want to ensure that the
version PRODUCT_VERSION is installed by anaconda.

Change-Id: I2681123ec508d11d90264f914fa25a68b6e5e7bb
Closes-Bug: #1509313
(cherry picked from commit 29ddb1e4a71e80c9ce3e77c71d382a165baf6523)

commit_message:
Fix for getting glance command list

Usual command uses xxxx --help for getting command list.
but glance case, it need to use help not --help.
For this purpose, adds if branch.
This patch is needed for complete/bash-completion switch.

glance is not viewed "Subcommands" list at header
  glance (Subcommands does not exist)
  http://docs.openstack.org/cli-reference/content/glanceclient_commands.html
  cinder (Subcommands exist)
  http://docs.openstack.org/cli-reference/content/cinderclient_commands.html
For this purpose, add glance switch for "Subcommands".

Change-Id: I33251e5ada49c6e2228d5d08aa5f2c5fd86da8bb
Closes-Bug: #1517756

commit_message:
Use SIGUSR1 to notify l3 agent of changing prefix file

It is common for all OpenStack services to use SIGHUP signal to
reload configuration and restart. This functionality, including
defining signal handler, is defined by oslo.service.

Meanwhile, this is currently not so for l3 agent. PrefixDelegation
class that is instantiated in L3NATAgent overrides handler for SIGHUP,
thus removing handler that was set in oslo.service.

The proposed solution is to use another signal, such as SIGUSR1,
instead of SIGHUP to notify l3 agent that a prefix file was
somehow changed.

Added a functional test for restarting L3 agent using SIGHUP.

Change-Id: I48eb4697a5fad97bcf08cfe1f80921a46d94029d

commit_message:
doc: document override_defaults phase

override_defaults phase was added to devstack in [1]
but documentation was pending. This patch adds the
same. For history around override_defaults, one can
refer to the mail thread [2]

Also fixes a small typo

[1]: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/167933/
[2]: http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-March/059621.html

Change-Id: I1b58ca0ce0e4b85a1dbd710b4c426606fd4dcf45

Interesting.

As I noticed, we need to do "pgrep -ag $PID" instead of "ps uhww -p $PID" for checking whole processes in the process group. Using ps only check whether the parent process goes down or not.

I saw the odd situation that n-cpu immediately stopped by kill command but the test was failed due to the error of "The following services are still running: nova-compute".

- n-cpu was killed immediately

http://logs.openstack.org/64/208064/6/check/gate-grenade-dsvm/2d6bac0/logs/grenade.sh.txt.gz#_2015-10-06_12_06_01_743

- Test was failed with "The following services are still running: nova-compute"

http://logs.openstack.org/64/208064/6/check/gate-grenade-dsvm/2d6bac0/logs/grenade.sh.txt.gz#_2015-10-06_12_08_07_849

Any thought?'}, {'account_id': 7293, 'date': '2015-10-07 13:05:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

The reason nova-compute is still considered running is that n-cpu.pid contains the pid of sg that is used to start nova-compute, not of nova-compute process itself. So if we send kill <n-cpu.pid>, nova-compute process won't be killed because sg doesn't pass signals to child processes.

(Here [1] you can see that nova-compute is actually running:

2015-10-06 12:08:07.823 | stack    26555  3.5  1.5 1843432 117024 ?      Sl   11:54   0:29 /usr/bin/python /usr/local/bin/nova-compute --config-file /etc/nova/nova.conf

)

That is why I modified the code that is writing to .pid file to put a correct pid there.

[1] http://logs.openstack.org/64/208064/6/check/gate-grenade-dsvm/2d6bac0/logs/grenade.sh.txt.gz#_2015-10-06_12_08_07_823"}, {'account_id': 7293, 'date': '2015-10-07 13:09:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Refactoring HP LeftHand Cinder Driver to be HPE

The HP LeftHand Cinder driver was recently refactored to be HPE.

The same refactoring is being done to the documentation with
this patch. It is being done because the company managing the HP
LeftHand Cinder driver is now Hewlett Packard Enterprise (HPE).

Closes-Bug: #1517648
Change-Id: Ibe4d4ff73591348fcf5997984e89d0a895172f6b

commit_message:
Change format of returning message

* When no free IP addresses are available in public network, Nailgun should
  return error message in a way which is acceptable by Fuel UI.
* Update corresponding unit test.

Change-Id: I9a2689c134bb4157d81f0749db495ec66d399118
Partial-bug: #1513774

commit_message:
Implement API service & dependencies

This patch rewrite puppet-gnocchi to be compliant with other modules.
It takes example at how puppet-aodh was written.

* Update init.pp to match Gnocchi requirements
* Update config.pp
* Add policy.pp
* Add storage.pp for carbonara
* Update db configuration
* Update keystone/auth.pp
* Add acceptance for API service for Centos only (not packaged on Ubuntu)
* Update unit tests

Change-Id: I82400b1e30f3700ab7a3d006b6bb143351bcc830

If we can't parse all of the files, then we end up with an object that only works some of the time and the owner of the object can't tell when it will or will not work. I think it's safer to let the object creation fail than to have potentially random failures later, particularly because the guarantee that we have right now is once the object is created all of its data is available so there is no error checking in place for the new cases where exceptions will be raised.

What sorts of situations do we have where an image file cannot be parsed properly? Maybe it would be better to fix the parser?"}, {'account_id': 18967, 'date': '2015-11-17 17:07:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Hi, Doug Hellmann, thanks for your review!

When the image type is ceph(rbd) or sheepdog, the parser will raise a ValueError certainly .

For example, we run the following command:
# qemu-img info -f rbd rbd:data/foo
image: rbd:data/foo
file format: rbd
virtual size: 10G (10737418240 bytes)
disk size: unavailable
cluster_size: 4194304

Since the disk size is unavailable, the parser will raise a ValueError. But this is a normal scenario for cluster storage system like ceph and sheepdog(maybe, there are other storage systems), because the disk size is meaningless to them.

For more information, please see the bug message I have reported. Thank you.'}, {'account_id': 18967, 'date': '2015-11-18 16:27:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Hi, everyone.

I think there is another way to fix this bug:

Since the 'disk size' info is always unavailable to cluster storage system like ceph and sheepdog, we should consider this as a normal scenario. We can modify the SIZE_RE from r"(\d*\.?\d+)(\w+)?(\s*\(\s*(\d+)\s+bytes\s*\))?" to r"(\d*\.?\d+)(\w+)?(\s*\(\s*(\d+)\s+bytes\s*\))?(unavailable )?". When parse the 'disk size' info ,if we find it is unavailable , then simply set it to zero or other reasonable value. This can keep my correction to a minimum.

Looks for your advice, I need your help, thank you very much!'}, {'account_id': 18967, 'date': '2015-11-20 09:02:31.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

This patch should be commited to cinder project.'}]

commit_message:
Fix the bug of can't get the desired image info

The current imageutils.QemuImgInfo class parse all the image info
at first, but if one of the info is unavailable, it would raise a
ValueError.

Sometimes, user only care one of the info which is really
available, but it may be failed because of the ValueError which is
caused by another unavailable info.

This patch resolves the problem by parsing each of the info separately,
so that getting the desired image info will not be influenced by other
unavailable info.

I have committed this patch to cinder, here is Change-Id:
Change-Id: Ic5f3b80e172baaafc07432319f8aa24bf117b392

Change-Id: I3692da15db6ee99edceb856643628b76a28ad270
Closes-Bug: #1516206

commit_message:
Add a negative test to bonding suite

Add a test that verifies bond config consistency
after deployment failure.

Change-Id: I1b06a81dbb99bec03f5a7de1d0c461c5ddbc7c5b
Closes-bug: #1516658

commit_message:
Update 'load_json' method in oslo.policy

If the format of policy.json file is not correct, we should give
explicit error messages.

It also works for other policy enforce strategy.

Change-Id: I1aa041a95b19c515a1df5dc048826e09e4abe93b

The whole commit seems wrong to me though it probably does the job. The problem that it is not aligned with initial agent design. Either this need to be implemented differently or design need to be updated. Most likly the best solution would be to write spec/BP describing file management on agent ant to sync our vision in that spec. The original design (described in Unified Agent specification) was that
1) function name passed to executor is the name of the function defined inside the script. In other words this is an ability to invoke individual methods within the script (like different entry points) rather than the script as a whole. This is not supported by bash but does supported by some other scripting engines. For example PowerShell. Then the syntax for invocation would be instead of foo(param) foo.method(param)
This commit uses function name for something different without introduction of that syntax but instead passing script name (e.g. key name in EP yaml) as a function name. It was assumed that user is free to use any name to refer to the script and now it it tide to some entity within that script (cookbook whatever).

2. Files were supposed to be shared across scripts. Agent puts all the files into single folder (usually using GUID-like names) and then for each script recreates its desired file structure (including subfolders) by symlinking files from that shared storage. As a result single file may be transferred once and reused across different scripts. This remained true for regular files but not for downloadable. In my understanding file manager should have downloaded files into cache folder and then symlinking downloaded root into script's folder rather than downloading files in place. And again this should not be bound to function name or script name"}, {'account_id': 13931, 'date': '2015-11-04 12:46:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

The bug was there since the files downloaded from an URL were stored in a files folder instead of a script name folder, as files transfered from murano are doing. These are the changes in the files_manager.py file.
However, that script name should arrive to Chef and Puppet executors, so that, they can find all cookbooks in the right place. Now everything is almost excellent. There is only one issue that I'd like to be addressed. For regular files we put all of them into single cache folder and then link subset of them for each script. So if several scripts require common file it doesn't need to be transferred twice. I'd like the same remain true for downloadable files (folders). In your code they are downloaded for each script separately (using script name as folder name) at the moment script is about to start. I think better behavior would be to download everything upfront using file_id as a folder name and then to link those folders on demand. The goal is that if there are 2 scripts and each of them require the same downloadable artifact (with the same URL) then it will be downloaded only once. Thanks!"}, {'account_id': 13931, 'date': '2015-11-17 12:00:29.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 13931, 'date': '2015-11-17 12:08:26.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-17 12:30:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Verified+1

commit_message:
Remove hardcoded destinations for puppet/chef processing engine

When cookbooks are transfered from murano to
murano-agent, they are stored in another folder
which chef/puppet expect.

Closes-Bug: #1508492

Change-Id: I1363e46d655c8a641a1fa404faadc5f652f9fce4

The update to openstack graphite data is now storing nulls instead
of high frequency zero values. Therefore, make the following changes:

1. use stats_counts instead of stats data, as this accesses the raw
counters
2. apply transformNull to all data series so that null -> 0 is handled
correctly
3. add a global drawNullAsZero=true to handle discontinuities

Thanks to jeblair and sdague for tracking this down

Change-Id: Idebc046d7d867d80e2afe1c4b86c526f9205d3d5

'}]
commit_message:
Fix dashboard graphite URLs

The update to openstack graphite data is now storing nulls instead
of high frequency zero values. Therefore, make the following changes:

1. use stats_counts instead of stats data, as this accesses the raw
counters
2. apply transformNull to all data series so that null -> 0 is handled
correctly
3. add a global drawNullAsZero=true to handle discontinuities

Thanks to jeblair and sdague for tracking this down

Change-Id: Idebc046d7d867d80e2afe1c4b86c526f9205d3d5
Signed-off-by: Ryan Moats <rmoats@us.ibm.com>

commit_message:
Modify baremetal_basic_ops test

Did few fixs for scenario baremetal_basic_ops test:
* removed redundant method that already exist in base class
* removed redundant ssh connection
* added additional timestamp verifications:
test checks only if file exists, but doesn't check size or data inside
* fixed conditions:
"if None > 0" doesn't work in python3

Change-Id: I16dfb807ddffa1e0987ff0e4baa2e6353523fc34

commit_message:
Fix Neutron flavor framework

Make flavor service profile store actual driver instead of
hardcoded dummy driver.  Ensure service type on flavor persisted.

Raise ServiceProfileDriverNotFound if non-empty driver is not part
of ServiceTypeManager providers.

Raise ServiceProfileEmpty if profile has neither a driver nor
any metainfo.

Raise InvalidFlavorServiceType if invalid service type passed.

Show flavors associated with a profile, not just profiles associated
with a flavor, to ease diagnosis when ServiceProfileInUse raised.

Create method to extract provider given a flavor for use with
neutron-lbaas plus tests.

Ensure various boolean forms accepted for enabled flag.

To enable in DevStack, add to local.conf:
enable_plugin neutron https://git.openstack.org/openstack/neutron
enable_service q-flavors

Add associated unit tests. Fix tempest api test that used invalid
LOADBALANCERS service type.

Change-Id: I5c22ab655a8e2a2e586c10eae9de9b72db49755f
Implements: blueprint neutron-flavor-framework

commit_message:
Add python-openstackclient required plugin package

python-openstackclient has plugin interface.
To generate full help message,
it needs to add plugin package (python-ironicclient) also.

Change-Id: I7b29b47eb58cb1aaa09aec9ca0ff3b8064ebd35d

There is one concern for the whole spec. This implementations required a node to have either BlockDevice driver or any other Cinder role. However is capable of running multiple backends in the same cinder-volume process. This means that actually the Block Device driver can co-exist on the same host with other drivers. The configuration becomes a bit more complicated in that case.

Allowing the user to have multiple Cinder backend would give a user more flexibility in storage configuration. (At least it is supposed to be that way.)

I do not have experience in running Cinder in multi-backend mode. So it would be great to hear from Cinder team if there is such expertise anywhere.'}, {'account_id': 3009, 'date': '2015-11-06 16:38:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 7132, 'date': '2015-11-19 11:56:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 16:

So as far as I see the main concern is that the fuel-core functionality should not be extending beyond where it is now and all new features should be added as plugins. 

This said the existing Cinder backends are still going to stay in core repository because I don't see any trend to extract them to plugins so far. That makes complete sense as Cinder is a core service to OpenStack and it's functionality should be available to user out of the box whether there are any plugins installed or not.

Essentially BlockDeviceDriver is just another Cinder storage backed driver which is today a best solution for workloads that require heavy disk operations. This backend has been in Cinder for quite a while and now is stable enough.

I appreciate the intent of moving to a better architecture faster but let's be realistic. We are talking about 8.0 timeframe so the soft code freeze will happen in one or two iteration (I'm not sure when exactly). This means that the current architecture will stay almost as it is right now, so why one storage driver is better as a plugin while others are out-of-the-box? And my second question is: is the plugin mechanism capable of providing the UI and Nailgun changes that are required and described in the spec?"}, {'account_id': 6677, 'date': '2015-11-19 17:43:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 16:

Just a general thought about this: it would really help if we have notion of 'native' plugins or 'core' plugins or whatever else that defines modules that are handled like plugins but included in the default ISO bundle and/or installed during the deployment of Fuel Admin node.

This would help us to reduce the opposition 'core vs plugins' and make shift to modular architecture at relatively low cost."}, {'account_id': 10391, 'date': '2015-11-19 20:18:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16: Code-Review+2

commit_message:
Check specific driver enabled in create_backup

Backend is already known so don’t need to use the default backend name
to check if the driver is initialized.

Change-Id: I797c75ca0eff574e3eb20dfedc8d5b64ca06a06a
Closes-Bug: #1515900

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Create gate-{name}-ansible-lint-tox

This is the replacement job for ansible-lint. Main differences here
are we expect tox to be properly setup, and we use zuul-cloner.  Zuul
cloner is needed because we need to preserve the directory name for
ansible-syntax to work properly.

Because of this, we needed to add a project variable to the tox
builder to properly change into the right directory.

Change-Id: Ia4bcfc8f7d86edbbeb74e926bf15119055433113
Signed-off-by: Paul Belanger <pabelanger@redhat.com>

[{'created': '2015-05-19 11:11:39.000000000', 'message': "Bump pbr cap to <2.0

Hacking's pbr cap of <1.0 is breaking things (see bug for a lot more
detail). Trunk hacking has already moved to the new pbr cap, but it
there is a backwards incompatible change on trunk
(I819d2069f169cabd1fcf333057a80790678e3745) that prevents us from
releasing 0.10.2 from there. So I created a 0.10.x branch and am
changing the pbr requirement here so that we can cut hacking 0.10.2 to
fix the bug.

Change-Id: I77f2b7e661c4de067e39596765d36a4463a2d143
Closes-Bug: #1456376
(cherry picked from commit bc4b1118e155784bc306c01733375ffec56b89b3)
"}]
commit_message:
Bump pbr cap to <2.0

Hacking's pbr cap of <1.0 is breaking things (see bug for a lot more
detail). Trunk hacking has already moved to the new pbr cap, but it
there is a backwards incompatible change on trunk
(I819d2069f169cabd1fcf333057a80790678e3745) that prevents us from
releasing 0.10.2 from there. So I created a 0.10.x branch and am
changing the pbr requirement here so that we can cut hacking 0.10.2 to
fix the bug.

Change-Id: I77f2b7e661c4de067e39596765d36a4463a2d143
Closes-Bug: #1456376
(cherry picked from commit bc4b1118e155784bc306c01733375ffec56b89b3)

[{'created': '2015-11-19 00:54:13.000000000', 'message': 'Stop nova driver delete failure on already deleted

The nova compute driver currently raises an exception if the
instance has already been deleted.

This patch logs a warning, but does not raise an exception when
the instance being deleted is not found.

Change-Id: I72e54297b925c5c6ce0dd711a33e19afc74ba37d
Partial-Bug: #1509706
'}]
commit_message:
Stop nova driver delete failure on already deleted

The nova compute driver currently raises an exception if the
instance has already been deleted.

This patch logs a warning, but does not raise an exception when
the instance being deleted is not found.

Change-Id: I72e54297b925c5c6ce0dd711a33e19afc74ba37d
Partial-Bug: #1509706

commit_message:
Allow customization of db sync command line

Add $extra_params parameter to neutron::db::sync class to
allow end users to add command line parameters to db sync command.

Change-Id: Ideeeb70115bcec8526444c142b54890707bfbf61
Partial-bug: #1472740

commit_message:
Error 500 trying to set empty desc. with LDAP

In ldap, an attribute cannot have an empty value.  This is the
same as having no attribute at all.  When doing an add or
modify of an object (project, user, etc.), check for empty
values, and reject them, or turn them into a modify/delete
if updating an attribute with a value.
Closes-Bug: #1282676
Change-Id: I1062e14b3e080f3b1548fc4e1354eae955a44b6b

commit_message:
Correct unscoped token request layout

The spec stated:

"A user may explicitly request an unscoped token by setting
the "scope" value of the token request to the string "unscoped."

However the code actually tests:

scope_data['unscoped'] = {}
which generates a dictionary, not a string.

This changes the spec to match the code, Since changing this now would
break anyone who coded to the original implementation.

Change-Id: I20bf026f1257161a2b11ceb95e812c4876f237ef
closes-bug: 1425174

commit_message:
Post-festum record of integrated Juno point release 2014.2.4

Release notes https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/ReleaseNotes/2014.2.4

Generated with:
version=2014.2.4
for project in ceilometer cinder glance heat horizon keystone neutron nova sahara trove
do
  commit=$( cd $project; git tag -v $version 2>/dev/null | awk '/^object / {print $2}' )

cat >> releases/deliverables/juno/$project.yaml <<EOF
  - version: $version
    projects:
      - repo: openstack/$project
        hash: $commit
EOF
done

Change-Id: Iaee3592686b1e49c045db61bd8dbe3e9d2083fb8

commit_message:
Add rabbit_ha_queues option

There are two ways for setting up RabbitMQ HA:

 1. Configure rabbit_hosts to multi rabbit hosts.
 2. Setting up a loadbalancer in front of RabbitMQ cluster,
    provide a unique address in rabbit_host

In current, rabbit_ha_queues option is controled by rabbit_hosts
if conditional statement. When users try the second method:
changing rabbit_ha_queues to true. If they don't set rabbit_hosts
, then current logic will not work.

This patch is aim to add an rabbit_ha_queues option, set it to undef by
default for backward compatbility.

Change-Id: I25fe5ef79d774757ee395efeaf4588efc56aada5
Close-Bug: #1485287

Not all install methods will manage these resources naturally.  For example, we're currently using this module with docker instead of packages. commit_message:
Remove POSIX users, groups, and file modes.

This patch removes the File, Group, and User resources of /etc/heat and
/etc/heat/heat.conf which should be delivered by packaging tools.  These
resources (mode, user, and group attributes) could be in conflict with
different OS packaging systems which isn't a desired result.

Change-Id: I5d49f3fc06df295700377eb66f883c9780959f96
Closes-Bug: #1458915

commit_message:
Add upgrade_levels configuration options

Add options to init.pp that allow the user to specify upgrade levels,
which pin the versions of the RPC communications between the various
compute services.

Change-Id: Ic04e3b9feac88c9b8b65f067761c1a6634d6d4eb
Closes-bug: #1477090

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

commit_message:
Fix ServiceTypeNotFound and MGMTDriverNotSpecified

These two exception classes are not coding correctly.
and It seems our unit test does not cover them.
So this patch adds two unit negative tests.

Change-Id: Ia02fac7bc644d849fb3409c72cd279957e44a3e7
Cloese-bug: 1515838

commit_message:
Initial commit - lay down basic structure

Add gemspec file, license, README, empty changelog, and empty library
files.

Note: the README proposes that this gem always be installed from the
master branch of the git repository. This would save us the trouble of
having make releases on the ruby forge and would mean that emergency
fixes added to the gem would be available immediately, but also means
that whenever we break it it breaks everything immediately. This
proposal is open to feedback and we can always revisit it.

Change-Id: I1490e3ec35235e057b3f0c13ae29b5913e7f8d49

commit_message:
Add openrc file creation to AIO script

This patch will add the creation of an openrc file
containing the credentials a user needs to use their
OpenStack deployment to the end of the AIO script.

Change-Id: I1353d9e1a3b026f0c6d56d6cfd2f0581866bed90

commit_message:
Update sample responses to list v3/endpoints and v3/policies

The GET v3/endpoints response does not contain 'name' but does
contain 'url'.

The GET v3/policies response contains the key of
'policies' rather than 'blob'. Also, it does not necessarily return
'Project_id' and 'user_id'.

Change-Id: Ib2ffc21d8ff2c2c9f80b8823628c55bacc455bf6

commit_message:
Swap the order of username deprecation

The attempt at a move to user-name is an exercise in churn, and is
filling everyone's logs with admonitions to change the name of their
variables - which does not work if they do. Swap this, effectively
reverting the attempt at a move. user-name will continue to work on
the off chance anyone started consuming that path, which is unlikely
because none of the consuming programs expose that as an actual option.

Closes-Bug: 1498247

Change-Id: I62d991fda1df63c9cbabfde2f6836bc031f5147c

commit_message:
Support for private IP addresses

The getting started sample will now run successfully on clouds that
use the private IP addresses as the public IP address.

Change-Id: I64680e96d7c05ea5e12bed4127eb0a48b6a66975

commit_message:
Change os-attach-interfaces to os-interface in Nova v2.1 API ref.

The current working API for interface attachment is
os-interface intead of os-attch-interfaces in Nova
V2.1 API.

Change-Id: I9b9d8f0d3d780888513b0fe7a5317ee8275f6503
Closes-Bug: #1517352

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-08-15 17:30:17.000000000', 'message': 'Manager support for projects acting as domains

Provide the Manager underpinnings for allowing a project to act as a
domain. Subsequent follow-on patches will build on this to allow
the creation or projects acting as domains at controller level and
provide full domain operations on such projects.

In this patch we provide manager support for creating a project
specifying a parent_id but not a domain_id. In the
controller layer we still normalize the domain_id if no
parent_id or domain_id were provided.

Co-Authored-By: Raildo Mascena <raildo@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>
Co-Authored-By: Rodrigo Duarte <rodrigods@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>

Change-Id: I21a89672dde27d9b9b34431e66235aac890e160e
Partially-Implements: bp reseller

commit_message:
Manager support for projects acting as domains

Provide the Manager underpinnings for allowing a root project to act
as a domain. Subsequent follow-on patches will build on this to allow
the creation of such projects acting as domains at controller level,
provide full domain operations on such projects and the creation of
sub-projects that act as domains.

In this patch we provide manager support for creating a project
specifying a parent_id but not a domain_id. In the
controller layer we still normalize the domain_id if no
parent_id or domain_id were provided.

Co-Authored-By: Raildo Mascena <raildo@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>
Co-Authored-By: Rodrigo Duarte <rodrigods@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>

Change-Id: I21a89672dde27d9b9b34431e66235aac890e160e
Partially-Implements: bp reseller

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Make delete_on_terminate Configurable

introduces a conf to support toggling whether delete_on_terminate
is set to true or false in the block-device-mapping.

Change-Id: I40213f257549bf8e34c4361f0fe3479cabe8449d
Implements: blueprint volume-delete-on-terminate

hi Nikola Dipanov, can you explain why this code is bad? if neutron does not set port quota, why nova need check free ports? when a tenant already has a lot of VMs, 'list_ports' is expensive!!!"}, {'account_id': 6835, 'date': '2015-04-22 08:27:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Excuse me, Nikola, are you talking about the codes of neutronv2 module?'}, {'account_id': 5511, 'date': '2015-04-22 09:50:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

this neturon API code is horrible, it will attempt to check quotas without reserving them which is completely useless.

I'd say that a better way to fix this is to remove quota checking altogether, at least we are being honest with oursleves, and avoid a useless expensive call"}, {'account_id': 8976, 'date': '2015-04-23 02:02:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

hi Nikola, I am very agree with you! Now in nova-api, it check quotas without reserving them, it might fail when nova-compute creates port, so this check is completely useless.
Neutron has a BP: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/neutron/+spec/better-quotas, but this BP still can't solve this problem!"}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2015-04-24 11:31:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I think that the approach taken here is ok and for this specific flow it saves an expensive API call.
The commit message could be updated to reflect that.'}, {'account_id': 12909, 'date': '2015-04-25 12:10:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

IMHO, this patch aims to optimize the case of no quota limited. No matter whether the quota reservation is supported, it's better to have. We can leave the race issue in another patch."}, {'account_id': 5511, 'date': '2015-04-27 09:13:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

From a Nova POV, if you still want to remove the expnsive call, IMHO replace the whole body of the validate_networks() method with a pass

What this gives us is that in some obvious cases, we get a nice quota exception back from the nova API making for a smoother UX. But in other's - instance goes into error without warning. 

I would argue that having quota exceptions sometimes pop back up from the API, and sometimes just error out the instance is even worse from a UX standpoint. I would always go for consistency and lack of surprise over this.

Still a -1 from me. Just remove the method altogether IMHO"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-27 13:31:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

Gary: even the commit message of the change that introduced it grants:

"""
A full fix would include reserving or creating the ports at
this stage, but there is no reservation mechanism in the
Neutron API, and port creation depends in some cases
on mac addresses only available on the compute manager
"""

and the discussion on the related bug is all over the place

https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1172808

making me think that this patch was the lowest common denominator aka "let's just land some code". That's not good and IMHO should have never landed because(as I describe earlier) it makes Nova only sometimes fail correctly. That's worst than being wrong consistently IMHO. Sadly - the revert of the original commit is no longer possible.

I say we take this out and fix it properly if we can - I will update the related bug too.

But bringing up the change that introduced it actually makes me thing of one more issue with this patch (see inline).'}, {'account_id': 8976, 'date': '2015-05-05 12:40:26.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 1501, 'date': '2015-05-05 14:10:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

commit_message:
Optimize validate_networks

Now neutron API does not provide reservation mechanism, so if a tenant has
a large number of ports, it check neutron port quotas with 'list_ports'
will be very expensive, a full fix would include reserving or creating the
ports at this stage, but port creation depends in some cases on mac addresses
only available on the compute manager, so it is better remove the quota
check in funtion 'validate_networks'.

Closes-bug: #1467728
Change-Id: Id815059695c787c86fd36888a531d5f8fefe5a80

Add resource OS::Nova::HostAggregate

Create resource OS::Nova::HostAggregate to support host aggregate operation
in nova.

blueprint support-host-aggregate

commit_message:
Repeat node installation after upgrade failure

If the node already belongs to Upgrade Seed environment, assume it was
moved there during upgrade procedure. Thus, no need to update node
attributes.

Use separate function to install such node, effectively repeating upgrade
procedure from the very beginning, replacing move of node with ordinary
provisioning.

Closes-bug: 1506405
Change-Id: I7052c0528027c15aee2342dea3b66fbef5f3e56e

commit_message:
Base install handler and compute install handler

Install handler is used in 2 cases:

* install additional controllers from scratch, based on controller node
  attributes from original environment
* reinstall compute node that failed to deploy after moving to the upgrade
  seed environment

Add compute handler for second use case.

Change-Id: Id0bfdf98637d7db70627f7d68bf0aa9da444c06e

commit_message:
Remove fedora-minimal/install.d/99-ramdisk

When the kernel gets installed on Fedora, the rpm post scripts call
"/bin/kernel-install" [1] to install it.  This is a script provided by
systemd.

However, in [2], Fedora ships a patch to kernel-install that makes a
call-out to /sbin/new-kernel-pkg -- the install script provided by
grubby [3]

Without grubby installed, systemd's kernel-install script goes off and
runs dracut plugins directly [4], which eventually creates the initrd.
For reasons that are not clearly explained, the initrd will end up in
a a "machine-id" sub-directory of /boot (possibly, so you can symlink
it?).  It is also called "initrd", even though it's an initramfs, for
historical reasons in dracut I think.

It is at this point that I think 99-ramdisk has been written to move
the generated initrd file back into /boot.  Later on, when we build
the image, we run grub-install and it picks up the kernel and the
initrd and installs everything.

grubby's new-kernel-pkg [6] it's very similar -- it uses dracut to
make the initramfs ... but in this case it is put in /boot and is
actually called initramfs.

The subtle change that led me down this path is that dracut has been
modified to have a "Recommends" for grubby for >F22 [7].  After
discussing this change with the author, it turns out it was *always*
intended to use the grubby-based kernel install scripts for Fedora --
our builds have been incorrect in not including the package.  The
author got sick of people removing the package and making unbootable
systems, hence the change.

Thus this removes the workarounds in 99-ramdisk and replace it with an
install of the grubby package.  grubby's kernel install script will
put the kernel & generated initramfs in /boot, and it will be
installed correctly via the usual grub install later when we build the
disk image.

I have built F22 & F23 fedora-minimal images with this and they boot.

[1] http://pkgs.fedoraproject.org/cgit/kernel.git/tree/kernel.spec#n1832
[2] http://pkgs.fedoraproject.org/cgit/systemd.git/tree/kernel-install-grubby.patch
[3] http://linux.die.net/man/8/new-kernel-pkg
[4] https://github.com/haraldh/dracut/blob/master/50-dracut.install
[5] https://github.com/systemd/systemd/commit/81516adcb71a47837544340f72eb8ee810274119
[6] https://github.com/rhinstaller/grubby/blob/master/new-kernel-pkg
[7] https://github.com/haraldh/dracut/commit/47ff68e78b3bbd01367948b5b9fe1cbaeb45f262

Change-Id: I1a6e45d04755515286b3d49f8280c16b527e2f48

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-08-07 12:47:10.000000000', 'message': 'Ensure l3 agent receives notification about added router

Currently router_added (and other) notifications are sent
to agents with an RPC cast() method which does not ensure that
the message is actually delivered to the recipient.
If the message is lost (due to instability of messaging system
in some failover scenarios for example) neither server nor agent
will be aware of that and router will be "lost" till next agent
resync. Resync will only happen in case of errors on agent side
or restart.
The fix makes server use call() to notify agents about added routers
thus ensuring no routers will be lost.

Closes-Bug: #1482630
Change-Id: Id08764ba837d8f47a28649d081a5876797fe369e

commit_message:
Ensure l3 agent receives notification about added router

Currently router_added (and other) notifications are sent
to agents with an RPC cast() method which does not ensure that
the message is actually delivered to the recipient.
If the message is lost (due to instability of messaging system
in some failover scenarios for example) neither server nor agent
will be aware of that and router will be "lost" till next agent
resync. Resync will only happen in case of errors on agent side
or restart.
The fix makes server use call() to notify agents about added routers
thus ensuring no routers will be lost.

This also unifies reschedule_router() method to avoid code duplication
between legacy and dvr agent schedulers.

Closes-Bug: #1482630
Related-Bug #1404743
Change-Id: Id08764ba837d8f47a28649d081a5876797fe369e

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-22 14:21:22.000000000', 'message': "Drop postgres jobs and add multinode to tempest check

This commit changes the tempest job layout to improve the value of
the tests run on each tempest commit. The postgres jobs are of
extremely questionable value on tempest commits, because making
changes to a test system which only interacts with the api using a
different db backend, eventlet for keystone, or the metadata service
instead of config drive shouldn't catch anything different compared to
the regular full job. So the postgres jobs are removed. The multinode
testing however will be of increasing importance and enables testing
additional functionality we weren't able to before. While it is still
non-voting we should move this to check to watch it. When it is deemed
stable enough for voting we should also add it to the gate queue for
tempest.

Change-Id: Ibf35d63c1e3c181cbc56e6c14f94d92d67e4ba51
"}]
commit_message:
Drop postgres jobs and add multinode to tempest check

This commit changes the tempest job layout to improve the value of
the tests run on each tempest commit. The postgres jobs are of
extremely questionable value on tempest commits, because making
changes to a test system which only interacts with the api using a
different db backend, eventlet for keystone, or the metadata service
instead of config drive shouldn't catch anything different compared to
the regular full job. So the postgres jobs are removed. The multinode
testing however will be of increasing importance and enables testing
additional functionality we weren't able to before. While it is still
non-voting we should move this to check to watch it. When it is deemed
stable enough for voting we should also add it to the gate queue for
tempest.

Change-Id: Ibf35d63c1e3c181cbc56e6c14f94d92d67e4ba51

commit_message:
Refactor os-client-config usage in from_config

This change allows the from_config factory function to better support
two angles from which it will most commonly be used.

1. When SDK is being used from within OSC, OSC will have obtained
configuration data from OCC and is better served by passing it directly
into SDK rather than SDK additionally accessing that data.

2. Direct users of the SDK, such as customer applications, are less
likely to have dealt directly with OCC and are better served by just
passing in the name of the configuration they want to run with.

Closes-Bug:1513920

Change-Id: I06f871b822e4b8b0cc8cc8db9e7ccff91f918e5a

commit_message:
Do Not Merge: Test test-accounts with roles

This commit generates a test accounts file with roles and configures
tempest to use the locking account creds provider instead of tenant
isolation. Things are hard coded so this isn't really a candidate for
merge in this state. This creates an accounts.yaml with 8 regular
user creds, 8 admin users, 4 users with the swift operator role, and
4 users with the swift reseller_admin role.

This omits setting a network devstack change:
I5fe09fdae2fb8082cb97fbcc46302939b328afbb tests using neutron to set
a network. It was easier to push a second patch that fix the if logic
in that change.

Change-Id: I76006bda934320e5ed7d2a694be50164ad8edc33
Depends-On: I709dce36210efa9038ce2d98328fc1740d9bf493

commit_message:
WIP Add a config option to load additional tests

As we move to having a more targetted tempest there may be other
projects which have tempest-like tests in tree that wish to include
these as part of a full tempest run. This adds a config option to load
additional tests as part of tempest's test discovery phase.

Change-Id: Ice56af429489254964af647cff4a6eb3e1c687d9

commit_message:
Do Not Merge: Test test-accounts with roles and networks

This commit generates a test accounts file with roles and configures
tempest to use the locking account creds provider instead of tenant
isolation. Things are hard coded so this isn't really a candidate for
merge in this state. This creates an accounts.yaml with 8 regular
user creds, 8 admin users, 4 users with the swift operator role, and
4 users with the swift reseller_admin role.

Depends-On: I709dce36210efa9038ce2d98328fc1740d9bf493
Change-Id: I5fe09fdae2fb8082cb97fbcc46302939b328afbb

commit_message:
Add tempest cli entry point

This commit adds a tempest binary to run tempest. The intended purpose
is to enable running tempest directly where the tox job definitions or
run_tempest.sh doesn't fit. It allows for some extra options on top of
those scripts such as a blacklist file. The entry point itself just
calls the testr command, however it abstracts away some of the manual
steps when calling testr directly. For example, the entry point will
look at the config file and determine whether running in parallel is
appropriate or not.

Change-Id: I5be007ec19d2c97c362c24db32810b0c0286a12f

commit_message:
Install Ceph in F23 without FORCE_CEPH_INSTALL=yes

We can successfully install Ceph Hammer release in latest Fedora 23.
So add f23 in ceph installation's distro whitelist and do not
need to use 'FORCE_CEPH_INSTALL=yes' to install ceph.

Change-Id: I0a87acbd4dc11886b80daa85c74f848b6f488634

commit_message:
Fix group mapping for glance_store

The project in launchpad is glance-store:

https://bugs.launchpad.net/glance-store/

So fix the group mapping so that changes in gerrit are reflected in
launchpad.

Change-Id: I2d9dde8d78b4da1dc6da8bc5ffe23b96ab9bb7a7

commit_message:
Fix H404/405 violations for remaining

There is a lot of H404/405 violations in Tempest now, and that leads
difficult to migrate the code to tempest-lib or the other projects'
repos. This patch fixes these violations for remaining.

Change-Id: I3abac40ebb33836980c119d59bc97f035b213c0a

commit_message:
Add admin_state_up attribute to Create LoadBalancer

The API Reference guide does not mention the admin_state_up
attribute in the Request Table for LBaaS v2 Create Load Balancer.
The following patch adds this information.

Change-Id: Id192740f064a1388f31f3471b211180f872b9068
Closes-Bug: 1517276

commit_message:
Fix H404/405 violations for api tests(3/3)

There is a lot of H404/405 violations in Tempest now, and that leads
difficult to migrate the code to tempest-lib or the other projects'
repos. This patch fixes these violations for api tests of compute.

Change-Id: Id6346f6a4a46dea56319ab482a4f499d0de098f9

commit_message:
Add an additional group_by field for node_region

While we don't explicitly have the node region listed as a separate
metadata field the build_node has the prerequisite information. This
commit adds dynamic generation of creating this group_by field in
the rest api by filtering the build_node field. It can be disabled
just like any of the other fields so if you don't want this displayed
or it doesn't provide value in your configuration it can be disabled.

Depends-On: I3c5eaa01653e713b634000f6cc07697636351e9d
Change-Id: Ic2db389d77385db1006c0f34828882710b5e08fb

commit_message:
Unbreak test_created_router_interface (heat)

The test become broken after 49c0fe5630d0eb8dbc95b2df8f147fa3a33830ca.
This change adds the missing variable.

The test failed with:
AttributeError: 'NeutronResourcesTestJSON' object has no attribute
'ports_client'

Change-Id: Ib5b8391ee86ce0797f2935e75c2a7e92200ee3d1

commit_message:
Fix skip_checks in live_migration

use cls.skipException instead of skipTest
if there are less then 2 compute nodes

Change-Id: I1a3b5db3389777dd5e73e53419280918b9b97ed2

[{'created': '2015-11-19 22:17:51.000000000', 'message': 'Only pass timeout to requests if we have a value

The requests documentation says that None is a valid value to pass,
but infra gets exceptions saying a float is needed if None is passed.

Rather than play roulette, only pass the argument when we have a value.

Change-Id: I3fcf60dd2f3350045b824899ac48b02809452a4b
'}, {'created': '2015-11-19 22:21:13.000000000', 'message': 'Only pass timeout to requests if we have a value

'}, {'created': '2015-11-19 23:59:12.000000000', 'message': 'Only pass timeout to swift if we have a value

commit_message:
Only pass timeout to swift if we have a value

swiftclient does not have the built-in None detection that keystoneauth
has, so we have to do it ourselves.

Change-Id: I3fcf60dd2f3350045b824899ac48b02809452a4b

Our current capacity is 56.

commit_message:
Send 50% less debug information when executing cmd

The current code prints out the command it runs twice: once in
'create_process' or 'execute_rootwrap_daemon', and once after the
command has finished executing and a return code is returned. Since this
is synchronous, there is no need to print the command twice in a row, so
this patch deletes the latter one, leaving only the exit code to be
printed.

This patch also refactors the surrounding code to make it more readable.

Change-Id: I22289f838dbc3956a777a78c882e4d5f1e725d0e

commit_message:
Add unit tests for direct_client

Add tests for direct_delete_account, direct_get_object, retry
Tests to validate possible argument calls of direct_put_object
Extend FakeConn to support chunks in response

Change-Id: I00cbc6c535ed8b3fb29bc07fdc51fdbb1220ff10
Signed-off-by: Ganesh Maharaj Mahalingam <ganesh.mahalingam@intel.com>

Including only 'active' agents to send l2pop messages has implications:

For example if an agent is down in the control path, but its datapath is intact, then all tenant VMs on that node cannot continue to communicate to other tenant VMs on other nodes, because this l2pop active_network count refinement fix, would result in tunnels torn down on te datapath from other active agents to these inactive agents.

Until the inactive agent is brought up, there will be datapath disruption for all tenant traffic from that host to elsewhere.

Am not sure if it is good to have such a coupling between datapath and controlpath.

Leaving it to other reviewers to pour their opinions."}, {'account_id': 9361, 'date': '2015-10-29 17:50:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-10-29 22:00:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

@Armando and @vivek:

I add inline comments in the code. 
And besides that, I would like to compare the code change here.

a) The code before patch [1].
Agent was filtered at [2] and [3] by SUPPORTED_AGENT_TYPES.
Agent was double checked with agent_ip at [4].
As a result, only L2 agent with agent_ip will be handled.

b) The code after patch[1].
Agent was NOT filtered at [2] and [3] by anything, so all agents are returned(metadata, l3, dhcp...)
Agent was filtered by agent_ip at [4].
As a result, only L2 agent with agent_ip will be handled.

c) The code in this review.
Agent was filtered at [2] and [3] by agent_ip.
Agent was double checked with agent_ip at [4].
As a result, only L2 agent with agent_ip will be handled.


No matter a) or b) or c) will not break use case and old test case.
But in b), I think the returned value of [2] and [3] are changed. And it is not what the original code want to do. Besides that, useless log will be printed at [5]. So, we have this review.

Could you please reconsider your -1 based on the comment above?
